g2:c.RULE.g2:a.TEXT: whenever any protools-authored-item X is moved and when the item Subject that is protools-subject-of-authored-item X exists then conclude that the _protools-x-offset of X = (the item-x-position of X - the item-x-position of Subject) and conclude that the _protools-y-offset of X = (the item-y-position of X - the item-y-position of Subject)

c.PROTOOLS-DOCUMENTATION-DETAILS.ua.PROTOOLS-DESCRIPTION:
This class is provided to help you document items in your application. Specifically, you use an instance of this class to describe the purpose of an item, and provide additional information on each attribute. Documentation for each attribute includes the name of the attribute, the public/private status of the attribute, a description of the attribute, and (for class definitions only) the allowable values for the attribute. You enter the attribute information by editing the structure in the protools-attribute-description.
When you clone an instance of a protools-documentation-details from the protools palette, drop it near the item you wish to document. This will create a permanent relation between the item and the details object, and also initialize the protools-attribute-description slot. If the item is a class definition, if you modify the definition of the class, the protools-attribute-description will be automatically updated to reflect the current attributes of the class.

g2:Structure.g2:sa.DESCRIPTION: use this field to describe the general purpose of the class definition documented by the class details object

g2:Structure.g2:sa.ALLOWABLE-VALUES: A sequence containing the attributes attribute-name (symbol), public (truth-value), allowable-values (text) (for class definitions only), and description (text), that documents the attributes of the associated item.

c.PROTOOLS-DOCUMENTATION-DETAILS.ua.PROTOOLS-DESCRIPTION: This relation links a protools-authored-item (such as a to-do reminder or instance details) to an item that is the subject of the authored item. You can use this relation allows you to find all the items with to-do reminders, by iterating over each protools-to-do-reminder and looking for the item that is protools-subject-of-authored-item to the to-do reminder. An item can have many associated authored items, but an authored item can only be associated to one item by this relation.

c.PROTOOLS-DOCUMENTATION-DETAILS.ua.PROTOOLS-DESCRIPTION: This class is used to define keyboard and mouse shortcuts. Each accelerator you define is automatically installed into the kb-configuration system table. To define a new accelerator, clone a protools-accelerator (keyboard icon) from the protools palette. Specify the attributes described below, and then user the menu choice to activate your accelerator (see turn-accelerator-off and see turn-accelerator-on).

g2:Structure.g2:sa.DESCRIPTION: A native action, such as go-to-subworkspace, or the label of a user menu choice that will be activated by this accelerator.

The class to which this accelerator applies. If the accelerator applies to kb-workspace, the applicable class should be given simply as 'workspace'. This attribute is used only when the accelerator is a keyboard shortcut. It is not used when the accelerator is a mouse gesture.

A text describing the keyboard or mouse gesture for this accelerator, such as the name of a single key (f10, h, escape), or a combination involving modifier keys (control + f5, shift + any mouse button, control + alt + any mouse button.)
An attribute used to turn the accelerator on or off

Sequence templates are a special kind of documentation template used to expand sequences. You use a sequence template when you want to generate text for each member of a sequence. The text of the template is applied to each member of the sequence. In addition, the sequence template defines a separator to print between elements of the sequence, and texts that can appear before and after the sequence. The sequence template defines initial and final texts, which appear before the first and after the last element of the sequence. The template can also define a text that is printed if there are no elements in the sequence. See protools-expand-template for more information about the expansion of templates.

g2:Structure.g2:sa.DESCRIPTION: A text to be included before the first element of the sequence.
A text to be included after the final element of the sequence.
A text to be included between elements of the sequence.
A text to use if the sequence has no elements.

The various procedures named by the attributes of this object can be changed to customize the documentation. Consult G2 Protools User's Guide for details.

The chapter number, read-only, determined by the position of the chapter in the protools-chapters of the associated book (see protools-book).
A short text that will be the root of file names generated for this chapter.

The name of a procedure that returns the list of items to be documented in this chapter. It takes two input arguments, a sequence of symbols containing the names of the target modules to be documented, and a client object. See protools-collect-class-definitions for an example of a item collection procedure.

The name of a procedure that takes two arguments, the item to describe and the client, and returns a structure containing information about the given item. See protools-describe-class for an example of a description procedure.
The name of a procedure used to add cross-references.
The name of the template to be printed at the top of each file associated with this chapter.
The name of the template to be printed at the bottom of each file associated with this chapter.
The name of the template for the navigation bar on the first page of this chapter.
The name of the template for the navigation bar on every page of the chapter, except the first and last page.
The name of the template for the navigation bar on the last page of the chapter.
The name of the template for the chapter number and name, on the first page of the chapter.
The name of the template used to print the entries in the summary of chapter contents, on the first page of the chapter.
The name of the documentation template to be used to expand each item included in this chapter.
Contains the number of files generated for this chapter, after the documentation generator has been run (read-only).

g2:c.BORDERLESS-FREE-TEXT.g2:a.TEXT:
In 5.0 Rev. 4 and higher, ProTools has been divided into two modules: protools and ptroot. This module, ptroot, contains definitions for objects in protools. It does not require authorization.
This two-module structure allows you to deploy KBs developed with ProTools without the need to purchase additional ProTools licenses. ProTools objects, such as documentation details, comments, protools books, etc. no longer need to be stripped when you delete the ProTools module; instead, they are preserved as long as your KB requires ptroot.
To prepare your KB for deployment, delete the module ProTools, but NOT ptroot. Then, re-arrange the module hierarchy so your KB requires ptroot, where previously it required ProTools.
To re-introduce ProTools, merge the ProTools module (protools.kb) into your deployment KB, and re-arrange the module hierarchy so your KB requires protools, where previously you substituted ptroot.
